Class Interval

java.lang.Object
  js.Disposable

All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Runnable
public class Interval
extends Task

Represents tasks that may be run periodically when set intervals.

A task of this class, as a runnable task, can be run by either its function version returned from its Task.getFunction() method or a call to its run() method. Besides, it can also get its function run in an interval periodic like what Js.setInterval(JsFunction, Number) does with a simple call to its set(Number) method, or cancel the periodic execution with a call to its clear() method like what Js.clearInterval(Object) does.

A subclass of this class must make sure that its function version, method run() and function being periodically run are all executing the same code.

Author:
J.J.Liu (Jianjun Liu) at http://www.jscripter.org
See Also:
Js.setInterval(JsFunction), Js.setInterval(JsFunction, Number), Js.clearInterval(Object), Timeout

Constructor Detail

Interval

protected Interval()

The default constructor.

A subclass must override run() to make the task runnable when its constructor invokes this one, because this constructor sets the Task.funct field to a function that invokes the run() method.

Since:
1.0
See Also:
run()

Interval

public Interval(java.lang.Runnable r)

Constructs from an existing runnable object.

This constructor sets the Task.funct field of this task to the function of the argument task. Note that, the run() method has been designed to simply invoke the Task.funct function. Override it with caution in a subclass where this constructor is invoked.

Since:
1.0

run()
